               <p>HENRY HOLE. I am a <rs id="t18280529-253-viclabel1398" type="occupation">barge owner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-253-victim1366 t18280529-253-viclabel1398"></join>. On the 11th of May I had some porter on board to go to Canterbury - the prisoners were <rs id="t18280529-253-deflabel1399" type="occupation">employed on board</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-253-defend1364 t18280529-253-deflabel1399"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-253-defend1365 t18280529-253-deflabel1399"></join>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-253-person1367">
                  SAMUEL 
                  BLYTH
               <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1367" type="surname" value="BLYTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1367" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1367" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Thames Police-surveyor. On the 11th of May, at 2 o'clock in the morning, I saw a light on board the Brigg barge, and saw a can handed down from the deck; I went on board and found Saffery on the deck; I said "What have you there?" He said,"Porter and a general cargo;" I went into the hold and found a spile in the porter cask - I said, "You have been spiling a cask, and I saw a can handed down;" Austin, who was below, said it was necessary to spile casks - I searched for the can, and said it was very odd I could not find it; I went down a second time with Dean, the master, and found the can under a sack, with a quantity of porter in it - I found a gimblet on Austin, and a piece of a different spile; the gimblet was wet, and<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182805290107"></xptr>fitted the hole in the cask; Austin said, "We were very dry, and thought no harm of taking a little porter."</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BARRY. Q. Does not the beer work at times? A. Yes; they then make a hole in the top of the cask, but this was in the head; their work is hard.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Were they at work there? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-253-person1368">
                  WILLIAM 
                  CARTER WESTCOTT
               <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1368" type="surname" value="CARTER WESTCOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1368" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1368" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a cooper and examined the cask; there was a hole in the bilge and a spile in the head, where we never allow a spile to be stuck; it was not in that state when it left Messrs. Trueman and Co., my employers.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-253-person1369">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BELL
               <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1369" type="surname" value="BELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1369" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1369" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Messrs. Hanbury's, and filled the casks; there was no spile in them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-253-person1370">
                  THOMAS 
                  MORRIS
               <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1370" type="surname" value="MORRIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1370" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-253-person1370" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Blyth; I saw Saffery hand the cask into the hold; I am certain he was the man: I was not above two yards from him; Austin was below.</p>
               <p>HENRY HOLE. They were hard-working men; I am so convinced of their honesty that I will take them into my employ again.</p>
               <p>
